
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `loginctl` baraye control kardan `systemd-logind`, ke service-e modiriat session va vorood karbar ast, be kar miravad. Ba `loginctl` mitoonid karbar-ha ra list konid, session-ha ra modiriat konid, va system ra khamush ya restart konid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `loginctl list-users` --> 🧑‍🤝‍🧑 List kardan hameye karbar-haye system.
    🔹 `loginctl list-sessions` --> 💻 List kardan hameye session-haye fa'al.
    🔹 `loginctl show-session [ID]` --> 🔍 Namayesh etela'at kamel dar morede yek session be moshakhas.
    🔹 `loginctl terminate-session [ID]` --> 🚪 Baste session be moshakhas.
    🔹 `loginctl poweroff` --> ⛔️ Khamush kardane system.
    🔹 `loginctl reboot` --> 🔄 Restart kardane system.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ loginctl list-users

    🔹 List mikone hameye karbar-ha ro.

    $ loginctl show-session 2

    🔹 Namayesh mide etela'at kamel session ba ID 2.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ loginctl terminate-session 2

    🔹 Session ba ID 2 ro mibande (agar shoma dastresi dashte bashid).

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `loginctl` command is used to control `systemd-logind`, which is the system service that manages user logins and sessions. With `loginctl`, you can list users, manage sessions, and shut down or reboot the system.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `loginctl list-users` --> 🧑‍🤝‍🧑 List all users on the system.
    🔹 `loginctl list-sessions` --> 💻 List all active sessions.
    🔹 `loginctl show-session [ID]` --> 🔍 Show detailed information about a specific session.
    🔹 `loginctl terminate-session [ID]` --> 🚪 Terminate a specific session.
    🔹 `loginctl poweroff` --> ⛔️ Shut down the system.
    🔹 `loginctl reboot` --> 🔄 Reboot the system.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ loginctl list-users

    🔹 Lists all users.

    $ loginctl show-session 2

    🔹 Shows detailed information for session with ID 2.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ loginctl terminate-session 2

    🔹 Terminates the session with ID 2 (if you have the required permissions).
